items.title: Morning Mail: the ‘terrifying’ impacts of US aid cuts; Trump threatens Iran as US fleet nears; PM pushes for progress on gun buybacks
items.standfirst: Want to get this in your inbox every weekday? Sign up for the Morning Mail here, and finish your day with our Afternoon Update newsletterGood morning. A year since the Donald Trump administration abruptly slashed foreign aid funding, Australian charities still grappling with the impacts say the cuts have resulted in preventable deaths.Closer to home, Anthony Albanese is set to push states over the looming gun buyback scheme prompted by the Bondi beach terror attack – despite staunch opposition to the plan from Queensland and the Northern Territory.‘Not radical, it’s fair’ | The government could make deep emissions cuts and restructure an ailing federal budget by taxing polluting companies for the damage they cause to the planet, new analysis claims.Foreign aid cuts | A year ago, the Trump administration ripped billions of dollars from aid projects around the world. The loss of critical funding is having an ongoing effect on Australian aid groups.Gun buybacks | Albanese will push the national cabinet to thrash out details of the looming gun buyback program on Friday – even as Queensland and the NT refuse to sign up. The government has also offered to delay the start of a $2bn scheme for early intervention autism services in a bid to secure an overdue deal at the national cabinet meeting from states on hospitals and disability funding.Coalition breakup | Sussan Ley has said David Littleproud turned down her offer for last-minute peace talks ahead of parliament’s return next week, but the Nationals leader says a time will be scheduled after the party’s upcoming leadership contest.Protests | Sources say the New South Wales government is considering further changes aiming to curtail protests in the Sydney CBD – as the premier, Chris Minns, points to the “unnecessary burden” demonstrations place on public safety.‘Not Writer’s Week’ | A grassroots group in Adelaide has scrambled to pull together an entirely new literary festival for the city in just two weeks after this year’s Adelaide Writers’ Week was cancelled amid controversy. Continue reading...

items.title: Knife-wielding man charged over allegedly threatening paramedics, patient
items.standfirst: H e is accused of trailing an ambulance carrying his alleged victim.
items.content: A man faces multiple charges in Adelaide today after allegedly stabbing another man before assaulting paramedics treating him.Events began at 1.30pm yesterday in the south-west suburb of Netley when emergency services were called to reports of a stabbing at Marion Road.Police found a 32-year-old man with stab wounds to his legs.READ MORE: Melbourne youth gang members on notice after police warningHe was taken to hospital with non-life-threatening injuries.It is alleged that when the victim and paramedics arrived at the Royal Adelaide Hospital, a man attempted to enter the ambulance, armed with a knife and making threats.There was no further stabbing and no one was injured. The suspect fled the scene in a white Porsche, with Victoria registration plates, which was tracked to the South Eastern Freeway at Mount Osmond.The suspect, a 27-year-old Victorian man was arrested without incident after the car was found stopped on the side of the road.READ MORE: 'Speed and violence': Trump threatens Iran with 'armada' attackHe faces numerous assault charges and is scheduled to appear in an Adelaide court today.Police do believe the incident is not random.Anyone with information should call Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 0000, or make a confidential online report.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

items.standfirst: P olice responded after the man allegedly jumped the counter and attacked three workers.
items.content: A man will face court in Adelaide today after allegedly biting a police officer on the ear in a KFC outlet overnight.Police were called to the fast-food restaurant on Pulteney Street, at the end of the city's central Rundle Mall, just before 11.30pm.They were told a man was refusing to leave the store and was causing a disturbance.READ MORE: Vodafone calls to SA Police Assistance Line hit by 'technical difficulties' It's alleged that after police were called, the man jumped the counter and attacked three employees.When police confronted him, the man allegedly punched a police officer and then bit him on the ear.The 23-year-old Bridgewater man was arrested and charged with a string of offences, including assaulting police.READ MORE: Evacuees told 'don't go home' as bushfire warnings downgraded He is set to appear in court today.The police officer required treatment for facial injuries but SAPOL said he remained in high spirits.The three fast food workers were not physically injured in the attack but were left shaken, police said.NEVER MISS A STORY: Get your breaking news and exclusive stories first by following us across all platforms.Download the 9NEWS App here via Apple and Google PlayMake 9News your preferred source on Google by ticking this box hereSign up to our breaking newsletter here

items.title: Melania Trump's $57m doco on track to bomb at the box office
items.standfirst: A new movie is coming out starring one of the world's most famous people, but it doesn't seem like anyone cares.
items.content: A new movie is coming out starring one of the world's most famous people, but it doesn't seem like anyone cares.Amazon's MGM Studios shelled out $57 million for the rights to Melania, a documentary about First Lady Melania Trump.But days before its release, Australian audiences appear completely disinterested.READ MORE: Enormous bruise spotted on Donald Trump's hand At its one screening this Friday at Sydney's Hoyts Warringah Mall, not a single ticket has been sold. In Cronulla, one person is going.At three cinemas in Melbourne, nobody has reserved a seat. Two tickets have been sold at a fourth.Most people don't buy movie tickets several days ahead of time, so the true reception won't be known until Friday.But a lack of pre-sales does indicate a lack of interest. The colossal sum is way beyond what movie studios usually pay for a documentary. READ MORE: Donald Trump appears to mix up Greenland and Iceland four timesCynics have suggested the bidding war between big Hollywood players for the film stemmed from a desire to curry favour with the administration.In the US, the movie is opening in more than 1500 cinemas.The Hollywood Reporter cites sources claiming Amazon has spent another $50 million on promoting the film.But even the most generous projections of how the film will fare at the box office indicates Amazon is set to lose tens of millions of dollars on the project.President Donald Trump is spruiking the project on his social media platform Truth Social."MELANIA, the Movie is a MUST WATCH," he said."Get your tickets today – Selling out, FAST!"READ MORE: Barron Trump may have saved woman's life, court hears The minute-long trailer of the film shows Mrs Trump walking into various events and generally looking glamorous."Here we go again," she said to the camera at the start of the trailer.But the trailer does not reveal much about the First Lady herself, who, despite her many public appearances, lives a relatively private life.The documentary was shot in the 20 days leading up to the second Trump inauguration.A premiere for the movie is set for the recently renamed Trump-Kennedy Centre tomorrow.The film was directed by Brett Ratner, the Hollywood filmmaker behind blockbuster hits like Red Dragon, X-Men: The Last Stand and the Rush Hour franchise.Melania is his first movie since six women accused him of sexual misconduct in 2017.He is now working on Rush Hour 4 at the behest of Donald Trump.READ MORE: Has Trump really ended eight wars?
